Beethoven is respected for one reason: the upper-classes insecurity about taste. Beethoven appeared when music became widely distributed. This is how he became revered - he became the go-to for posh people to name-drop in conversation, and those they talked to copied them - and it snowballed from there. It is not a coincidence that the most name-dropped composers - Bach, Beethoven and Mozart - were from around the same time: 1750-1800. Much like how Shakespeare is not the best writer in history - he was just the one that was fashionable to namedrop - funnily enough, also in the late 1700s. This was a time of cultural pretention. People who try to seem sophisticated and cultured by singing the praises of whoever it is that makes them seem so. These people are clueless.

The standard of conducting was set for all time by what we know about Beethoven. Fluid tempo, a singing quality, and a unity in toto are the natural resultants of all true composing. We know this is what the old masters, Bach, Mozart, Haydn, etc. would have wanted. And what we do know about their methods suggests it. This is the essence of all musical expression. This ideal was given example in Habeneck's orchestra, and purified and articulated by the progressive party of the War of the Romantics, and then passed on to every great conductor of the latter half of the 19th, and the next, century. Richter, Bulow, Mottl, Weingartner, Strauss, Mahler, etc.

Ban all supporters of HIP from teaching in music schools, and mandate Richard Wagner's (PBUH) essay On Conducting as part of the curriculum for every student.

>>114208199
1st Shape:
Barre the index finger across all six strings at the 8th fret play the 10th fret A string with your ring finger, 10th fret D string with your pinky, and the 9th fret G string with your middle finger. When barring with the index finger, try rolling it a bit to the side of the finger (just slightly) and curl the other fingers in, being careful not to accidentally mute strings that are meant to ring out. Your fretting hand thumb should be right around where the skunk stripe on some necks is (the middle) and it should be roughly aligned with your fret hand middle finger, so that you could touch your thumb to your middle finger fingertip if the neck weren't in the way.

Shape 2:
Same thing but lift your middle finger off the G string.

Shape 3:
Press the 3rd fret of the A string with your index finger. Barre across the 5th fret of the D, G, and B strings with your ring finger. Mute the High E string with the underside of your index finger. Mute the Low E string with your index finger fingertip.

Shape 4:
Press the 3rd fret of the A string with your index finger. Press the 5th fret of the D string with your ring finger, and the 5th fret of the G string with your pinky finger. Press the 4th fret of the B string with your middle finger. Make sure your fingers are curled in comfortably as before and not unintentionally muting other strings. Mute the High E string with the underside of your index finger, which lays flatter against the strings compared to your other fingers.

Hope that helps.

In USA, it's not uncommon for people to be unfamiliar with classical music, or to have trouble distinguishing between different Scandinavian countries. However, that doesn't mean that the influence of classical music on electronic music subgenres in these countries should be overlooked.

In the case of dungeon synth, a subgenre of electronic music that originated in the 1980s and 1990s, it's interesting to consider the distinct musical influences that have shaped its development in different parts of Scandinavia.

For example, in Sweden, it's been suggested that the keyboard and organ music of ABBA, the iconic Swedish pop group, had a significant influence on the development of dungeon synth in the country. ABBA's music is known for its catchy and upbeat sound, and it's not surprising that it would have an impact on other musical genres.

On the other hand, in Norway, it's been suggested that the music of composer Grieg had a greater influence on the development of dungeon synth. Grieg was a 19th century Norwegian composer known for his romantic and nationalistic style, and his music often featured prominent piano and orchestral elements.

While these two examples may seem quite different at first glance, it's worth noting that the use of organs and keyboards is a common feature in both ABBA's music and dungeon synth, and it's possible that this shared element contributed to the influence of ABBA's music on Swedish dungeon synth.

Overall, it's fascinating to consider the various musical influences that have shaped the development of different subgenres of electronic music, and how these influences can vary from one country to another.

Dungeon synth is a style of Electronic music that focuses on evoking epic, atmospheric soundscapes associated with fantasy and medieval settings. Artists primarily utilize synthesizers, keyboards, and drum machines to create Ambient and orchestral textures, with vocals, samples, acoustic instruments, and lo-fi production also occasionally employed. Due to its instrumental nature, dungeon synth musicians concentrate on storytelling through music and create specific sceneries often inspired by mythology, literature of fantasy writers such as J.R.R. Tolkien, video games, and tabletop RPGs like Dungeons & Dragons. The term was coined on March 17th, 2011, in Andrew Werdna's first post on Dungeon Synth Blog, where he described it as "the sound of the ancient crypt."

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114201732
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ytNp0gikre0
Early influences of the genre include Berlin School acts such as Tangerine Dream and Klaus Schulze creating layered, synthesizer-led textures inspired by space and futurism. Jim Kirkwood took these hypnotic soundscapes and used them to produce fantasy-oriented atmospheres. Another wave of influence came from the Neoclassical Darkwave sound of Dead Can Dance, who developed their compositions using synths and drum machines. Dark Ambient and Martial Industrial were also important influences, as plenty of early examples of dungeon synth were guided by those styles.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114201783
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=85I6tnjsb9I
The first dungeon synth artists emerged in the early-mid 1990s in the wake of the Norwegian Black Metal scene. Mortiis started his solo career after he departed from Emperor and embraced simply-produced, medieval-esque compositions. Varg Vikernes often utilized ambient/dungeon synth interludes on Burzum records, and after his imprisonment, he released his two "prison albums," Dauði Baldrs and Hliðskjálf, which were recorded using a synthesizer and a tape recorder. Other significant projects from the first era include Depressive Silence, who dabbled in ethereal, lush, and lo-fi soundscapes, and Summoning, who accentuated their Symphonic Black Metal sound with keyboards and drum machines.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114201815
https://ppowerplant.bandcamp.com/album/stump-soup
In the 2000s, dungeon synth experienced a decline, where acts discontinued or went in different directions with their style. The genre began regaining interest in the early 2010s, with blogs and sites such as Andrew Werdna's Dungeon Synth Blog and the Dungeon Synth Archives Youtube channel introducing the genre to new listeners. Werdna's Blog in particular helped establish a more formal description of its sound. Projects which contributed to the revival wave, such as Erang, Lord Lovidicus, and Fief, were inspired by the 1990s acts, while Bandcamp became the successor to the tape trading community. Due to its rising popularity in the late 2010s and 2020s, dungeon synth artists began experimenting with creating different, more specific moods with Winter Synth (Yearner, Inoriand) exploring cold soundscapes while Comfy Synth (Grandma's Cottage, Earthencloak) delved into cozy, nostalgic atmospheres, dropping the epic aesthetic.

>>114184516
some cool sound design in this, you are talented. there are some mix issues that i probably wouldn't be able to describe without sitting down with you and looking at the project itself. the percussion feels weak; part of the weakness is in the mixing, another part is in the arrangement/stylistic choices. a sampled break would do wonders for the tune; when working entirely synths, tempering the synthetic nature with the character of live percussion can really do wonders. as for the synths, it feels like there's some gnarly resonance in the mid-high region. it's really, really tough to mix an entirely-synth track well. judicious use of eq and bell filters to make each synth track occupy its own distinct place in the mix could be useful. panning is also a hidden dimension through which space can be carved out. pic related; it's from an ancient textbook on mixing, but a useful way to think about space in a mix; 3 axes: volume, frequency, and stereo field. tldr, would focus on mixing fundamentals: eq and parallel compression. good track.

>>114183708

>>114178718
immediately noticed the punchiness of the bass/kick. that's an area where a lot of these /prod/ tunes fall flat. the auxillary percussion could stand out better in the mix. you could afford to bring the bass out a bit more. don't be afraid to add some saturation/more compression to it. the playing is in general real clean, but some parts where rhythm could be tightened up a bit. some of the shredding guitar could be upped in the mix too. i think this would really benefit from a wider stereo image, which would be in line with the proggy feel. cool tune, you've got chops, just need to tighten up the performance/mixing a bit.

posts.com: I love the Velvet Underground. I’m sure a lot of you love the Velvet Underground. They’re near universally recognized as possessing incredible influence and songwriting, and I’m not here to dispute that. What’s interesting, though, is how lucky they were. If a small band like the VU wasn’t picked up by Warhol of talked up by Bowie, it’s hard to imagine them getting attention, and later their due critical praise. One has to wonder how many bands we just forgot, even if they were great, and nobody gives them a shot now because there’s no rym to tell everyone how great they are. It just doesn’t sit right with me, and I’d like to think I’d know a band like that when I hear it, but I might not.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114213808
I wouldn't say it was luck. they knew what they were doing and the art scene was spreading by word of mouth rapidly at this point. Warhol was also big fan of silver apples for example but they didn't take off like VU for obvious reasons. Joe Byrd ran in a scene parallel to warhol on the opposite coast. I'm not discrediting these artists that made very original and influential music but they couldn't touch the staying power of VU

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114213808
Yup, that's a true fact of life there. Think about all the virtuoso musicians we'll never hear because they didn't get the chance to be recorded. IIRC, Hendrix himself said there were guitarists better than him back in Seattle that never got a chance to shine. And then think about how the titans of classical, Bach, Beethoven, Mozart, etc, were said to be incredible improvisors. A lotta shit we miss, but at least there's good stuff to listen.

And weirdly enough, the Velvet Underground was somewhat famous for being an 'underground' band. By the time of 1970's Max's Kansas City gig, they acquired a reputation as a legendary band. People like Orson Welles and Salvador Dali were said to have at least attended one Velvet Underground gig. Bowie I think is the number 1 reason why they're so influential today, he rescued Lou with Transformer and covered VU songs early on. He was one of the first people in England to hear of them, as he heard the acetate for the Banana Album. Life has a large part of blind luck to it, lmao. Zappa and the Mothers only got a record deal because Tom Wilson thought they were a decent blues rock band after only listening to Trouble Every Day.

I follow what I enjoy. What I think's interesting, and what makes me feel good, or at least captivated.

Going through the motions of what other people say you're supposed to do has always made me feel very depressed. If I had more of a tolerance for doing that, I'd probably be more professionally successful.

It's a losing game with music, though. If your music is too popular, people will call you a pleb. If your music is too obscure, people will call you a tryhard. If it's in between, people will say "babby's first ___." If your music is too emotional, people will call you a fag or an incel. If your music is too tough people will call you a white trash chud. There's an insult for literally everything. Like what you like, because regardless, some people will connect with you over it, and some people will hate you for it. So you might as well identify with stuff you actually like.

>>114208602
I love this album, it's my favorite. If you saw it at #1 on a large 81 album chart, that's mine. It's dark, grand, apocalyptic, the guitars are beautiful, the lyrics are interesting, I love everything about it. It's glam rock for the post-punk/indie era. The lyrics are poetic, emotive, and dark. It's stylish, and the band is so passionate. There's a strong romanticism to them. I also love the s/t debut, but this is where they were at their best. I discovered them in my teens, and a decade later, I love it even more than I did back then.

I would also make a strong recommendation for their four reunion albums, which are nearly at this level. Here's a song that particularly stands out to me: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qks__ZNvhiw

Their middle period is decent, but I'm significantly less enthusiastic about it than I am about the first two albums, or the four reunion albums.

If you want things somewhat like this, I could recommend Pulp's His N Hers and This Is Hardcore, Gaz Coombes' solo material (he was the vocalist of Supergrass), the Manic Street Preachers' early material, Echobelly, and James.

>>114208830
It seems like Suede is surprisingly polarizing. They're very much genuine, heart-on-your-sleeve, and a little melodramatic. This is a lot different than a lot of other Britpop bands like Pulp and Blur, who were funnier, more tongue-in-cheek, more cynical, and a little more post-modern. I think that gives people a comfortable emotional distance that helps those bands go down easy. Suede is like an intense, heavy shot of emotion, which seems to turn some people off.

anon please practice with a tuner, you can become in-tune very quickly but you need to do long notes with a tuner. for everyone in this thread who wants to acquire a good sound: look up "high tones eugene rousseau pdf", click the first link, start doing the exercises, and do an exercise where you start with the most beautiful note you can currently play and try to get an identical sound on all notes on the instrument, starting with the closest ones a half-step away. the note should take 8 beats of 60 bpm. then spend the rest of the practice session doing whatever you want. when you lift other saxophonists, lift their timbre as well, not just the notes they're playing.

Vaporwave has continued to remain interesting for a variety of reasons. It's use of retro graphics, neon colors, and slowed-down or pitch-shifted samples of music from the 1980s and 1990s makes it distinct from other genres. This aesthetic has had a lasting impact on popular culture, influencing fashion, art, and even advertising.

Another reason vaporwave is still interesting is that it is a genre that is constantly evolving and being reinterpreted by new artists. Despite being a relatively niche genre, vaporwave has inspired numerous sub-genres and spin-offs, such as future funk, mallsoft, and hypnagogic pop, which have added new layers of complexity and innovation to the genre.

Vaporwave has also gained a cult following online, with a vibrant community of fans and artists who are dedicated to exploring and celebrating the genre. This community has helped to keep vaporwave alive and relevant, even as other trends have come and gone.

Overall, vaporwave's enduring appeal can be attributed to its unique aesthetic, its ability to evolve and adapt, and its dedicated community of fans. Even in 2022, vaporwave remains an interesting and influential genre that continues to inspire and captivate listeners around the world.
